Your `-subj` value is valid OpenSSL syntax:

```bash
-subj "/CN=services.company.com/OU=DEVE/O=AFVL/L=Baabdat/ST=Matn/C=LB/UID=2ce4293f-5cdf-4215-afd8-ef045f2025b2"
```

So the error usually means OpenSSL is **not receiving the subject exactly like that**.

The most common reason is: **you are running this in Git Bash / MSYS / MinGW on Windows**. Git Bash automatically converts paths that start with `/`, so:

```bash
/CN=services.company.com/OU=DEVE/...
```

may be transformed into something like:

```bash
C:/Program Files/Git/CN=services.company.com/OU=DEVE/...
```

Then OpenSSL says:

```text
subject name is expected to be in the format /type=value/...
```

because the string no longer starts correctly with `/CN=...`.

Use this:

```bash
MSYS_NO_PATHCONV=1 openssl req -new -sha256 \
  -key privatekey.pem \
  -out csrreq.csr \
  -subj "/CN=services.company.com/OU=DEVE/O=AFVL/L=Baabdat/ST=Matn/C=LB/UID=2ce4293f-5cdf-4215-afd8-ef045f2025b2"
```

Or in Git Bash:

```bash
export MSYS_NO_PATHCONV=1

openssl req -new -sha256 \
  -key privatekey.pem \
  -out csrreq.csr \
  -subj "/CN=services.company.com/OU=DEVE/O=AFVL/L=Baabdat/ST=Matn/C=LB/UID=2ce4293f-5cdf-4215-afd8-ef045f2025b2"
```

If you are using Windows PowerShell or CMD, the command should usually work as-is, but you can also try single quotes in PowerShell:

```powershell
openssl req -new -sha256 `
  -key privatekey.pem `
  -out csrreq.csr `
  -subj '/CN=services.company.com/OU=DEVE/O=AFVL/L=Baabdat/ST=Matn/C=LB/UID=2ce4293f-5cdf-4215-afd8-ef045f2025b2'
```

Also make sure you are not copying the `$` symbol. The `$` is just the terminal prompt, not part of the command.
